In 2001, a secret memo concluded that President George W. Bush had the authority to wage preemptive war against terrorists and countries not linked to 9/11.
The memo stated there were "no limits" on the president's war authority, paving the way for potential Iraq invasion without Congressional approval.
The memo argued for military action to protect the US from terrorist threats.
Alberto Gonzales faced scrutiny for his role in creating legal frameworks that led to torture and abuse.
The debate over torture scandals involving Iraqi detainees continues, with calls for accountability and transparency.
